XML_CASESUMMARY.SUMMARY:
This two-vehicle collision occurred a couple of hours after noon during daylight. The collision occurred on a three-lane undivided rural roadway with one lane in each direction and a center turn lane. The pre-crash roadway for eastbound traffic is a level curve to the right with bituminous paving. For westbound traffic the pre-crash roadway is straight and level approaching a curve to the left. The weather was clear and dry. The center lane was covered in old sand from a previous snow a few weeks prior. The posted speed limit for the roadway is 40 kmph (25 mph).
Vehicle one (V1) was a 1997 Acura 2.2 CL 2-door coupe driven by a seventeen (17) year old male with one passenger. V1 was traveling eastbound at a high rate of speed into the easterly curve to the right. Vehicle two (V2) was a 2005 Toyota Corolla sedan driven by a fifty two (52) year old male with one passenger. V2 was traveling in a westerly direction approaching the curve to the left. V1 lost control in the curve and drifted into the center turn lane, when he tried to steer back into his original lane, his tires lost traction in the loose sand and the vehicle continued to travel to the left into the oncoming lane, rotating clockwise. The front of V2 impacted the left side of V1. V1 pushed V2 backwards approximately 18 meters (60 feet). V1 came to rest facing northwest in the center lane. V2 came to rest facing northwest in lane one. Both vehicles were towed due to damage.
The critical pre-crash event for V1 was coded: this vehicle traveling, over the lane line on left side of travel lane. The critical reason for the critical event coded driver related factor: too fast for curve/turn. The driver estimated his speed while in the curve to be 80 - 97 kmph (50 - 60 mph). He was on his way from school to see a movie and drives this route weekly. Associative factors for V1 were: speeding, loose sand & gravel on roadway and under-inflated tires.
The critical pre-crash event for V2 was coded: other vehicle encroachment; from opposite direction, over left lane line. The critical reason was not code to this vehicle. The driver of V2 was listening to the radio while on his way from home to a store. The driver has a learning disability and suffers from short term memory loss. He takes the medications Lovastatin and Hydrochlorthizide.
